    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>How many bundles of shingles do I need per square?</summary>
        <p>For standard three-tab asphalt shingles, you need three bundles per roofing square (one square equals 100 square feet). For heavier architectural or dimensional shingles, you may need four to five bundles per square depending on the manufacturer and shingle weight. Always check the manufacturer's specifications printed on the bundle wrapper, which will state the coverage per bundle. Add 10% to 15% extra for waste due to cuts, starter strips, and mistakes.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How do I measure roof pitch from the ground?</summary>
        <p>You can estimate roof pitch from the ground by standing back and using a pitch gauge app on your smartphone, or by measuring from inside the attic. In the attic, hold a level horizontally against a rafter, measure 12 inches along the level, then measure the vertical distance from the end of the level down to the rafter. If the vertical distance is 6 inches, your pitch is 6:12 (6 inches of rise for every 12 inches of horizontal run). Common residential pitches range from 4:12 to 8:12.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How much does a roof replacement cost?</summary>
        <p>The average roof replacement cost in the United States ranges from $8,000 to $15,000 for a standard 1,500 to 2,000 square foot home using architectural asphalt shingles, including labor and materials. Three-tab asphalt shingles cost $4 to $6 per square foot installed, architectural shingles cost $5 to $8 per square foot, metal roofing costs $8 to $14 per square foot, and tile roofing costs $10 to $20 per square foot. Labor typically accounts for 40% to 60% of the total cost, varying by region, roof complexity, and the number of layers being removed.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How long do asphalt shingles last?</summary>
        <p>Standard three-tab asphalt shingles last 15 to 20 years under normal conditions. Architectural (dimensional) shingles typically last 25 to 30 years, and premium or designer shingles can last 30 to 50 years. Metal roofing lasts 40 to 70 years, clay or concrete tile lasts 50 to 100 years, and slate can last over 100 years. Actual lifespan depends on climate, ventilation, installation quality, and maintenance. Extreme heat, frequent storms, and poor attic ventilation can shorten shingle life significantly.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Can you install new shingles over existing shingles?</summary>
        <p>In many jurisdictions, you can install one layer of new shingles over an existing single layer, which is called a re-roof or overlay. This saves on tear-off and disposal costs, typically $1,000 to $2,000. However, most building codes prohibit more than two total layers of shingles. Roofing over existing shingles is not recommended if the current roof has extensive damage, uneven surfaces, or moisture problems, as these issues will transfer through to the new layer. A full tear-off allows inspection of the roof deck for rot and damage.</p>
      </details>
